results.notes:
On consolidated sandy soil in a maritime chaparral habitat with manzanitas

Thallus not evident. Apothecia black, plane, round, with thick raised persistent margin. Disk roughened, matte, epruinose. Margin epruinose, shiny when wet. Epihymenium black with aeruginose tints, hymenium hyaline, IKI+blue, hypothecium brown. Exciple C+R. Algae only present in small amount at base of apothecium. Medulla tissue was not I+B using Lugol’s, but I might need to use straight Iodine?

Spores simple, hyaline, narrowly ellipsoid, about 13×5µm.

There are not many C+R species without epilithic thallus in Sonoran Flora. The spores on this one are too wide for L. diducens.

results.notes: I just joined this site. Hello all! I (our family) have been collecting mushrooms for over 40 years in the country of Georgia. There are so many of them that we don’t pick, simply due to not knowing what they are. I have decided to expand my personal knowledge of mushrooms and would like to have a place (a website) where I can share images and information and consult with professionals. Hope this is the site! :) Here are some images of the latest mushrooms that we found that are not familiar to us. Please help with identification. This particular one was found in a grassland, right next to mixed woods (predominantly Oak though). There was only one of them. I did some research and it seems like it might be Amanita Macerisolum. Don’t know much about it and couldn’t find info on edibility.

This material should be compared with that in observation 367443.

I start the microscopic analysis with observation 367443. As usual the material was very scarse, since the only way to get some apothecia is to scrape off with the knife, and I exhaust it before getting definitive conclusions, but at the time I was convinced that it was some unusual Lecidella, mainly based on the views of the apothecial sections and the asci stain in phloxine and lugol. However, I had no oportunity of looking to the internal structure of the spores. due to the lack of samples.
After, starting the microscopic analysis of the material of this observation, after sometime I got the impression of “deja vu” and realized that this material should be of the same species than in the above cited observation. Again I arrived to the point of having only one apothecium left for analysis and I used it to get photos of the asci stained with Cotton blue in lactic acid (CBLA), where one can clearly see that some of the spores are 1-septate while others don’t.
Some other things have contributed for my initial misinterpretation of the material under observation. For instance, the following: in the “Notes of the descrition of the genus Lecidella in CNALH” (see http://lichenportal.org/portal/taxa/index.php?taxon=51989)it is written:
“Notes: The genus can be determined (easily) by the ascus-type, because the Lecidella-ascus is so far only known from this genus”. However, I found very problematic to distinguish it from the so-called Catillaria-ascus which is characterized to be " uniformly K/I+ blue apical dome".
Now, looking to the spores I think that this can fit in the genus Catillaria and at the following link I could find a species that is promissing:
http://www.afl-lichenologie.fr/...

Primer registro de esta especie para el país, determinado el 5/06/2016 por Chivatá Teodoro y Arias Camila, en el Humedal La Conejera Bogotá, Colombia.

Basidioma estipitado, lignicola, principalmente gregario, en ocasiones solitario o cespitado, no higrofano, el Píleo mide entre 5 a 7 cm de diámetro, hemisférico en un principio, luego pasa a ser plano convexo con el centro umbonado, orbicular (vista apical). Margen recto, entero y ligeramente ondulado, de superficie glabra, viscida y brillosa, que luego pasa a ser seca y opaca, de color rojo que tiende a oscurecerse hacia el borde, con escamas fasciculadas originadas por restos del velo universal que forma un círculo a modo de collar cerca del borde. Himenio con lamelas y lamélulas, se encuentran próximas entre sí (apretadas), adnadas a ligeramente uncinadas, anchas, de borde liso, lamélulas atenuadas, de color café claro principio, después gris violáceo y finalmente púrpura negruzco, arista entera, blanquecina. Contexto homegeneo y hueco. Esporada de color marron oscuro.

Estípite de 4-8 cm de largo x 0.4-0.5 cm de ancho, cilíndrico, central, sub-bulboso y con tomento basal con cordones miceliares (rizomorfos), de color blanco con zonas de color naranja rojizo que se intensifica con el tiempo, pruinoso. Se engrosa ligeramente hacia la base. De consistencia fibrosa. Sin olor o sabor apreciable. Basidiosporas elipsoidales, lisas, de paredes gruesas, con poro germinal.
